{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949050401/1213.xml":{"full_text":"DISPLAY OF OLD FIREARMS\nat n6me Hardware\nQuite an array of old rifles and\npistols is on display in the show\nwindow at *the Nome Hardware\nthis week. The guns belong to in\ndividuals who have allowed the:,\nancient possessions to be display\ned, and although the historical\nbackground of each was no.\nlearned, the display is well worth\nviewing.\nFOR\nDEPENDABLE\nSERVICE\nCall Main 5\nCITY CAB\nPostpone Fish\nTrap Legislation\nI ^/P) Special Washington Service)\nWASHINGTON Chairman\nBoykin <D.-Alu.> of a House fish\neries sub-committee has announc\ned that no further action on legis\nlation to abolish fish traps in Ala\nj ka will be taken until after the.\nsub-committee visits the Territory\ni next Summe\nDelegate Bartlett of Alaska pn\ntC' ed the action, contending testl-.\ni mony on pending bills is complete\nj and that nothing would be gaincl\nby a committee visit.\nHe pointed out the voters of the\nTerritory a year ago voted over\ni whelmingly to abolish the traps.\nBoykin told Bartlett he has been\ninformed many fishermen have\nchanged their vi^ws since the elec\ntion and he feels the sub-commit\ntee should hear testimony in the\ni Territory.\nPIONEER WATER DELIVERY\nSAND and GRAVEL\nGENERAL HAULING\nBOX 17 MAIN 94 or MAIN 70\nJACK LENCER\nWatchmaker\nBox 625 Nome, Alaska\nWE CARRY LARGE ASSORTMENT OF\nFINE LIQUORS, BEER AND WINE\nOut-of-Tovvn Orders Carefully Handled\nTHE NOME LIQUOR STORE\nL 4\nPing-Free Power!\n(CHEVRON\n1 SUPREME\nGASOLINE A\n\u00bbr r\nFor Today\u2019s High Compression Engines\nYou Can\u2019t Buy a Better Gasoline!\nFaster starts Smoother performance\nQuicker warmups Speedier getaway\nSTANDARD OIL COMPANY\nOF CAUFORNIA\n\u201cRecession Will\nRelief\ni 1 o consumers\u201d\nWASHINGTON, <,P)_The Pres\nident of the United States cham\nber of commerce said yesterday\nhat a \u201crecession from postwar\npeaks\u201d of business is inevitable.\nHe added that it will bring \u201cover\ndue relief to millions of consum\ner,\nEarl O. Shrove, in the keynote\naddress of the chamber\u2019s 37th an\nnual meeting, also told some 2,500\ni business leaders:\n\u201cWhen the current readjustment\nhas run its course, and buying for\ni n ventory replacement revives,\nbusiness should find itself on a\nsounder and infinitely more satis\nfactory basis.\u201d\nThe shut to a more solid and\norderly pattern of prosperity\u201d will\nbe blocked or delayed, Shreve\nsaid, if the government raises\ntaxes and lays down economic\ncontrols\u2014as proposed by Presi\ndent Truman\u2014or embarks on a\npolicy of in-the-red financing.\n\u201cIt is self-evident to all think\ning men,\u201d he declared, \u201cthat the\nfederal budget should be balanced\nthrough the economy in spending\nI \u2014not through higher taxes.\u201d\nTwo other speakers at the first\ngeneral session of the four-day\nmeeting offered plans to bulwark\nprosperity, at home and abroad:\nB u s i n e s smen should give\n\u201cprompt attention to the task of\npricing consumers back into the\nmarket\u201d by lowering prices and\nbringing out new products, said\nHarry A. Bullis, board chairman\nof General Mills, Inc., Minneapo\nlis.\nA price decline is \u201cnaturlal and\ninevitable,\u201d Bullis said\u2014\u201cwe are\nlaying the groundwork for a long\nand sustained rise in the living\nstandard of America.\u201d\nAnd a Canadian, president Hen\nry C. Birks, of the Canadian cham\nber of commerce, Montreal, pro\nposed an \u201cABC\u201d committee of\nAmerican, British and Canadian\nbusinessmen to labor for the free\ning of world trade from currency\nand other trade barriers.\nHouse Returns\nLabor Bill To\nCommittee\n\u2022Continued from Page One'\nj tion forces needed to swing eight\nvotes overnight to put the Wood\nbill in the cooler.\nThey succeeded in getting the\nneeded margin although there was\none more vote cast today than in\nyesterday\u2019s ballot.\nThe motion to recommit was\nsupported by 193 Democrats. 18\nRepublicans and one American\nLabor member.\nVoting against recommittal\nwere 62 Democrats and 147 Re\npublicans.\nThe outcome served to take\nsome of the sting from the rebuff\nhanded to President Truman by\nyesterday's vote. He had v made\nTaft-Hartley repeal a key point of\nhis re-election campaign and\u2014af\nter yesterday\u2019s Maneuvering it\nappeared the administration could\nnot put it over.\nToday\u2019s vote salvaged another\nchance some time in the future.\nRep. Priest iD.-Tenn.), the Dem\nocrat \"whip\u201d or assistant leader,\nhad the job of rounding up the\nneeded votes for the over-night\nshift.\nBefore the ballot, even he ap\npeared to be uncertain whether the\nadministration could win. Priest\nwould say only that there appear\ned to be a \"fair chance.\u201d\nHangchow Falls\nWithout A Fight\n\n(Continued from Page One\u00bb\nenemy).\nThe Red radio reported deepen\ning thrusts into South China.\nThe last big American liner due I\nin Shanghai before May 23 also\nwas getting up steam at its pier\ni here today. The ship, the Ameri\ncan President Lines\u2019 General Gor\ndon, took aboard 1200 passengers,\nincluding some 800 Chinese going\nto Hong Kong. Only fifty Ameri\ni cans went aboard. A U. S. navy\nsj>okesman said it has ships avail\nable to evacuate the 1,650 Ameri\ncans still here, if necessary; and\ni that the navy will stay as long as\nneeded.\nThe U. S. consulate in Canton\nj meanwhile urged that all Ameri\ncan women and children leave the\ninterior cities of South China.\nPlanes may not be available to\nbring the mout later, it explained.\nMany of the Americans here\nwere crowding into the American\nDies From One\nPunch In Mouth\nCORDOVA, An Everett,\nWash., packer boat worker was\nfree today on $5,000 bond pending\na fall term of the grand jury.\nHe is Arne Johnson, 42, charged\nwith manslaughter in connection\nwith the one-punch death of\nGeorge Beyer, 24\u201e last Saturday.\nA coroner\u2019s jury Monday called\nthe death \u201cexcusable homicide.\u201d\nTestimony brought out that\nJohnson \u201cwent into the alley to\nsettle the matter\" reluctantly dur\ning an argument while the two\nwere drinking.\nBeyer, from Cordova and Val\ndez, was knocked out by a single\nblow to the mouth. Doctors were\ncalled, but Beyer failed to regain\nconsciousness.\nJohnson is employed by Gordon\nNelson on the packer boat New\nSunrise.\nClub, in mid-town, which has not\nbeen occupied by troops thus far.\nA. A. SANITARY COMPANY\nPhone MAIN 85\n\u201cFor Courteous, Efficient Service\u201d\nCome to the\nArctic Club\nCARNIVAL\nSee the Queen\nCrowned\nEnjoy the Games\nand Dancing\nPrizes for All\nHigh School Gym\nSat. Nite, May 7th.","height":"27156","width":"20252"}}
